content.explanation:
Splitting physics into branches makes an impossibly large subject manageable. Each branch tackles one part of "how the universe works."

**Classical Mechanics** — the physics of things moving: gravity, pushes, pulls, rolling, orbiting. A ball rolling down a hill, a car on a road, a planet orbiting the sun. {{viz:diagram-02}}

**Thermodynamics** — heat and temperature. Why an oven heats up, why a fridge stays cold, why you sweat when you're hot. Anywhere energy moves or spreads, this is the branch in charge.

**Electricity & Magnetism** — how electricity and magnets work, and how they're actually the same underlying phenomenon. Your phone battery, a compass, a bolt of lightning.

**Waves & Optics** — sound, light, vibrations. Why the sky is blue, why rainbows form, how a speaker turns electricity into sound.

**Quantum Mechanics** — the physics of atoms and electrons. At this scale the rules that work for a rolling ball stop applying, and a different set of rules takes over. {{viz:anim-01}}

**Modern Physics** — the extreme cases: speeds near light, nuclear reactions, particle physics, relativity. Black holes and nuclear energy live here.

Every branch, regardless of subject, follows the same method: observe, understand, predict. {{viz:chart-01}}
